# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ami-metering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:ami-metering/advanced-metering-infrastructure] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMR technologies include handheld, mobile and network technologies based on telephony platforms (wired and wireless), radio frequency (RF), or powerline transmission.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With touch-based AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer or data collection device with a wand or probe.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The device automatically collects the readings from a meter by touching or placing the read probe close to a reading coil enclosed in the touchpad.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] When a button is pressed, the probe sends an interrogate signal to the touch module to collect the meter reading.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The software in the device matches the serial number to one in the route database, and saves the meter reading for later download to a billing or data collection computer.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Since the meter reader still has to go to the site of the meter, this is sometimes referred to as "on-site" AMR.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Another form of contact reader uses a standardized infrared port to transmit data.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Protocols are standardized between manufacturers by such documents as ANSI C12.18 or IEC 61107.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMR hosting is a back-office solution which allows a user to track their electricity, water, or gas consumption over the Internet.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] All data is collected in near real-time, and is stored in a database by data acquisition software.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The user can view the data via a web application, and can analyze the data using various online analysis tools such as charting load profiles, analyzing tariff components, and verify their utility bill.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Radio frequency based AMR can take many forms.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The more common ones are handheld, mobile, satellite and fixed network solutions.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are both two-way RF systems and one-way RF systems in use that use both licensed and unlicensed RF bands.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In a two-way or "wake up" system, a radio signal is normally sent to an AMR meter's unique serial number, instructing its transceiver to power-up and transmit its data.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meter transceiver and the reading transceiver both send and receive radio signals.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In a one-way "bubble-up" or continuous broadcast type system, the meter transmits continuously and data is sent every few seconds.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This means the reading device can be a receiver only, and the meter a transmitter only.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Data travels only from the meter transmitter to the reading receiver.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are also hybrid systems that combine one-way and two-way techniques, using one-way communication for reading and two-way communication for programming functions.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] RF-based meter reading usually eliminates the need for the meter reader to enter the property or home, or to locate and open an underground meter pit.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The utility saves money by increased speed of reading, has less liability from entering private property, and has fewer missed readings from being unable to access the meter.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The technology based on RF is not readily accepted everywhere.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In several Asian countries, the technology faces a barrier of regulations in place pertaining to use of the radio frequency of any radiated power.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] For example, in India the radio frequency which is generally in ISM band is not free to use even for low power radio of 10 mW.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The majority of manufacturers of electricity meters have radio frequency devices in the frequency band of 433/868 MHz for large scale deployment in European countries.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The frequency band of 2.4 GHz can be now used in India for outdoor as well as indoor applications, but few manufacturers have shown products within this frequency band.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Initiatives in radio frequency AMR in such countries are being taken up with regulators wherever the cost of licensing outweighs the benefits of AMR.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In handheld AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer with a built-in or attached receiver/transceiver (radio frequency or touch) to collect meter readings from an AMR capable meter.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This is sometimes referred to as "walk-by" meter reading since the meter reader walks by the locations where meters are installed as they go through their meter reading route.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Handheld computers may also be used to manually enter readings without the use of AMR technology as an alternate but this will not support exhaustive data which can be accurately read using the meter reading electronically.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Mobile or "drive-by" meter reading is where a reading device is installed in a vehicle.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meter reader drives the vehicle while the reading device automatically collects the meter readings.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Often, for mobile meter reading, the reading equipment includes navigational and mapping features provided by GPS and mapping software.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With mobile meter reading, the reader does not normally have to read the meters in any particular route order, but just drives the service area until all meters are read.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Components often consist of a laptop or proprietary computer, software, RF receiver/transceiver, and external vehicle antennas.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Transmitters for data collection satellites can be installed in the field next to existing meters.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The satellite AMR devices communicate with the meter for readings, and then sends those readings over a fixed or mobile satellite network.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This network requires a clear view to the sky for the satellite transmitter/receiver, but eliminates the need to install fixed towers or send out field technicians, thereby being particularly suited for areas with low geographic meter density.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] There are also meters using AMR with RF technologies such as cellular phone data systems, Zigbee, Bluetooth, Wavenis and others.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Federal Communications Commission (FCC) licensed frequencies and others under FCC Part 15, which allows use of unlicensed radio frequencies.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] WiSmart is a versatile platform which can be used by a variety of electrical home appliances in order to provide wireless TCP/IP communication using the 802.11 b/g protocol.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Devices such as the Smart Thermostat permit a utility to lower a home's power consumption to help manage power demand.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The city of Corpus Christi became one of the first cities in the United States to implement citywide Wi-Fi, which had been free until May 31, 2007, mainly to facilitate AMR after a meter reader was attacked by a dog.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Today many meters are designed to transmit using Wi-Fi, even if a Wi-Fi network is not available, and they are read using a drive-by local Wi-Fi hand held receiver.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meters installed in Corpus Christi are not directly Wi-Fi enabled, but rather transmit narrow-band burst telemetry on the 460 MHz band.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This narrow-band signal has much greater range than Wi-Fi, so the number of receivers required for the project are far fewer.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Special receiver stations then decode the narrow-band signals and resend the data via Wi-Fi.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Most of the automated utility meters installed in the Corpus Christi area are battery powered.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Wi-Fi technology is unsuitable for long-term battery-powered operation.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] PLC is a method where electronic data is transmitted over power lines back to the substation, then relayed to a central computer in the utility's main office.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This would be considered a type of fixed network system—the network being the distribution network which the utility has built and maintains to deliver electric power.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Such systems are primarily used for electric meter reading.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Some providers have interfaced gas and water meters to feed into a PLC type system.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This technology was a spin-off of the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first fully automated, commercially available remote meter reading and load management system.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The primary driver for the automation of meter reading is not to reduce labor costs, but to obtain data that is difficult to obtain.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] As an example, many water meters are installed in locations that require the utility to schedule an appointment with the homeowner in order to obtain access to the meter.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In many areas, consumers have demanded that their monthly water bill be based on an actual reading, instead of (for example) an estimated monthly usage based on just one actual meter reading made every 12 months.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Early AMR systems often consisted of walk-by and drive-by AMR for residential customers, and telephone-based AMR for commercial or industrial customers.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] What was once a need for monthly data became a need for daily and even hourly readings of the meters.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Consequently, the sales of drive-by and telephone AMR has declined in the US, while sales of fixed networks has increased.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The trend now is to consider the use of advanced meters as part of an advanced metering infrastructure.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Originally AMR devices just collected meter readings electronically and matched them with accounts.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] As technology has advanced, additional data could then be captured, stored, and transmitted to the main computer, and often the metering devices could be controlled remotely.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] This can include events alarms such as tamper, leak detection, low battery, or reverse flow.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Many AMR devices can also capture interval data, and log meter events.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering infrastructure, or AMI is the new term coined to represent the networking technology of fixed network meter systems that go beyond AMR into remote utility management.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The meters in an AMI system are often referred to as smart meters, since they often can use collected data based on programmed logic.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The Automatic Meter Reading Association (AMRA) endorses the National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners (NARUC) resolution to eliminate regulatory barriers to the broad implementation of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution, passed in February 2007, acknowledged the role of AMI in supporting the implementation of dynamic pricing and the resulting benefits to consumers.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution further identified the value of AMI in achieving significant utility operational cost savings in the areas of outage management, revenue protection and asset management.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution also called for AMI business case analysis to identify cost-effective deployment strategies, endorsed timely cost recovery for prudently incurred AMI expenditures and made additional recommendations on rate making and tax treatment of such investments.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering systems can provide benefits for utilities, retail providers and customers.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Benefits will be recognized by the utilities with increased efficiencies, outage detection, tamper notification and reduced labor cost as a result of automating reads, connections and disconnects.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Retail providers will be able to offer new innovative products in addition to customizing packages for their customers.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In addition, with the meter data being readily available, more flexible billing cycles would be available to their customers instead of following the standard utility read cycles.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With timely usage information available to the customer, benefits will be seen through opportunities to manage their energy consumption and change from one REP to another with actual meter data.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Because of these benefits, many utilities are moving towards implementing some types of AMR solutions.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In many cases, smart metering is required by law (e.g.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the utility.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the customer.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Construction practices, weather, and the need for information drive utilities in different parts of the world towards AMR at different rates.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In the US, there have been significant fixed network deployments of both RF based and PLC based technologies.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] Some countries have either deployed or plan to deploy AMR systems throughout the entire country.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] By using a combination of AMR and energy analytics reports, SPAR were able to reduce energy consumption by 20%.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] AMI in Australia has grown from both government policy which sought to rectify observed market inefficiencies, and distribution businesses who looked to gain operational efficiencies.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In July 2008, there was a mandated program being planned in Victoria for the deployment of 2.6 million meters over a 4-year period.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The anticipated peak installation rate of AMI meters was 5,000 per day across Victoria.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] The program governance was provided by an industry steering committee.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] In 2009 the Victorian Auditor General undertook a review of the program and found that there were "significant inadequacies" in advice to Government and that project governance "has not been appropriate".
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] With the growing adoption of AMI meters and systems, AMR has been in decline in the U.S. electric utility sector.
[src:ami-metering/automatic-meter-reading] However, in the gas and water sectors, where it tends to be more expensive and complicated to replace meters, AMR remains prevalent, and some utilities continue to invest in new AMR meter deployments.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A **home network**, or **home area network** (**HAN**), is a computer network, specifically a local area network (LAN), that facilitates communication among devices within the close vicinity of a home.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Devices capable of participating in this network, for example, smart devices such as network printers and handheld mobile computers, often gain enhanced emergent capabilities through their ability to interact.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] These additional capabilities can be used to increase the quality of life inside the home in a variety of ways, such as automation of repetitive tasks, increased personal productivity, enhanced home security, and easier access to entertainment.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Other than a regular LAN that is centralized and uses Ethernet, Wi‑Fi, and Internet Protocol (IP), a home network may also make use of direct peer-to-peer methods as well as non-IP protocols such as Zigbee and Bluetooth.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Certain devices in a home network are primarily concerned with enabling or supporting the communications of the kinds of end devices residents more directly interact with.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Unlike their data center counterparts, these networking devices are compact and passively cooled, aiming to be as hands-off and non-obtrusive as possible.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A gateway establishes physical and data link layer connectivity to a WAN provided by a service provider.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Home routers provided by internet service providers (ISP) usually have the modem integrated within the unit.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] It is effectively a client of the external DHCP servers owned by the ISP.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A router establishes network layer connectivity between a wide area network (WAN) and the local area network of the residence.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] For IPv4 networking, the device may also perform the function of network address translation establishing a private network with a set of independent addresses for the network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] These devices often contain an integrated wireless access point and a multi-port Ethernet LAN switch.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A wireless access point provides connectivity within the home network for mobile devices and many other types using the Wi-Fi standard.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] When a router includes this service, it is referred to as a wireless router, which is predominantly the case.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A network switch permits the connection of multiple wired Ethernet devices to the home network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] While the needs of most home networks are satisfied with wireless connectivity, some devices require wired connection.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Such devices, for example IP cameras and IP phones, are sometimes powered via their network cable with power over Ethernet (PoE).
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A network bridge binds two different network interfaces to each other, often in order to grant a wired-only device access to a wireless network medium.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Controllers for home automation or smart home hubs act as a controller for light bulbs, smart plugs, and security devices.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Home networks may use either wired or wireless connectivity methods that are found and standardized on local area networks or personal area networks.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] One of the most common ways of creating a home network is by using wireless radio signal technology; the 802.11 network as certified by the IEEE.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Most wireless-capable residential devices operate at a frequency of 2.4 GHz under 802.11b and 802.11g or 5 GHz under 802.11a.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Some home networking devices operate in both radio-band signals and fall within the 802.11n or 802.11ac standards.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Wi-Fi is a marketing and compliance certification for IEEE 802.11 technologies.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] The Wi-Fi Alliance has tested compliant products, and certifies them for interoperability.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Low power, close range communication based on IEEE 802.15 standards has a strong presence in homes.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Bluetooth continues to be the technology of choice for most wireless accessories such as keyboards, mice, headsets, and game controllers.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] These connections are often established in a transient, ad-hoc manner and are not thought of as permanent residents of a home network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A "low-rate" version of the original WPAN protocol was used as the basis of Zigbee.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Home networks may consist of a variety of devices and services.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Personal computers such as desktops and mobile computers like tablets and smartphones are commonly used on home networks to communicate with other devices.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A network attached storage (NAS) device may be part of the network, for general storage or backup purposes.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] A print server can be used to share any directly connected printers with other computers on the network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Smart speakers may be used on a network for streaming media.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] DLNA is a common protocol used for interoperability between networked media-centric devices in the home, allowing devices like stereo systems on the network to access the music library from a PC on the same network, for example.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Using an additional Internet connection, TVs for instance may stream online video content, while video game consoles can use online multiplayer.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Traditionally, data-centric equipment such as computers and media players have been the primary tenants of a home network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] However, due to the lowering cost of computing and the ubiquity of smartphone usage, many traditionally non-networked home equipment categories now include new variants capable of control or remote monitoring through an app on a smartphone.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Newer startups and established home equipment manufacturers alike have begun to offer these products as part of a "Smart" or "Intelligent" or "Connected Home" portfolio.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Examples of such may include "connected" light bulbs (see also Li-Fi), home security alarms and smoke detectors.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] These often run over the Internet so that they can be accessed remotely.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Individuals may opt to subscribe to managed cloud computing services that provide such services instead of maintaining similar facilities within their home network.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] In such situations, local services along with the devices maintaining them are replaced by those in an external data center and made accessible to the home-dweller's computing devices via a WAN Internet connection.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Apple devices aim to make networking as hidden and automatic as possible, utilizing a zero-configuration networking implementation called Bonjour embedded within their line of software and hardware products.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Microsoft offers simple access control features built into their Windows operating system.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Additionally, a home server may be added for increased functionality.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] The *Windows HomeGroup* feature was introduced with Microsoft Windows 7 in order to simplify file sharing in residences.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] All users (typically all family members), except guest accounts, may access any shared library on any computer that is connected to the home group.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Passwords are not required from the family members during logon.
[src:ami-metering/home-area-network] Instead, secure file sharing is possible by means of a temporary password that is used when adding a computer to the HomeGroup.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] An MDM system will typically import the data, then validate, cleanse and process it before making it available for billing and analysis.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Furthermore, an MDM may provide reporting capabilities for load and demand forecasting, management reports, and customer service metrics.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] An MDM provide application programming interfaces (APIs) between the MDM and the multiple destinations that rely on meter data.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] This is the first step to ensure that consistent processes and 'understanding' get applied to the data.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Besides this common functionality, an advanced MDM may provide facility for remote connect/disconnect of meters, power status verification/power restoration verification and on demand read of remote meters.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Smart meters send usage data to the central head end systems as often as every minute from each meter whether installed at a residential or a commercial or an industrial customer.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Utility companies sometimes analyze this voluminous data as well as collect it.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] 5. detecting and reducing unbilled energy.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] This data not only helps utility companies make their businesses more efficient, but also helps consumers save money by using less energy at peak times.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Smart meter infrastructure is fairly new to Utilities industry.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] As utility companies collect more and more data over the years, they may uncover further uses to these detailed smart meter activities.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Similar analysis can be applied to water and gas as well as electric usage.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] According to a 2012 web posting, data that is required for complete meter data analytics may not reside in the same database.
[src:ami-metering/meter-data-management] Instead, it might reside in disparate databases among various departments of utility companies.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering policies can vary significantly by country and by state or province: if net metering is available, if and how long banked credits can be retained, and how much the credits are worth (retail/wholesale).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Most net metering laws involve monthly rollover of kWh credits, a small monthly connection fee, require a monthly payment of deficits (i.e. normal electric bill), and annual settlement of any residual credit.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering uses a single, bi-directional meter and can measure the current flowing in two directions.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering can be implemented solely as an accounting procedure, and requires no special metering, or even any prior arrangement or notification.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering is an enabling policy designed to foster private investment in renewable energy.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering originated in the United States, where small wind turbines and solar panels were connected to the electrical grid, and consumers wanted to be able to use the electricity generated at a different time or date from when it was generated.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The first two projects to use net metering were an apartment complex and a solar test house in Massachusetts in 1979.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Minnesota is commonly cited as passing the first net metering law, in 1983, and allowed anyone generating less than 40 kW to either roll over any credit to the next month, or be paid for the excess.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 2000 this was amended to compensation "at the average retail utility energy rate".
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This is the simplest and most general interpretation of net metering, and in addition allows small producers to sell electricity at the retail rate.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Utilities in Idaho adopted net metering in 1980, and in Arizona in 1981.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Massachusetts adopted net metering in 1982.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] By 1998, 22 states or utilities therein had adopted net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Two California utilities initially adopted a monthly "net metering" charge, which included a "standby charge", until the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) banned such charges.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 2005, all U.S. utilities were required to consider adopting rules offering net metering "upon request" by the Energy Policy Act of 2005.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of 2013, 43 U.S. states have adopted net metering, as well as utilities in 3 of the remaining states, leaving only 4 states without any established procedures for implementing net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] However, a 2017 study showed that only 3% of U.S. utilities offer full retail compensation for net metering with the remainder offering less than retail rates, having credit expire annually, or some form of indefinite rollover.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering was slow to be adopted in Europe, especially in the United Kingdom, because of confusion over how to address the value added tax (VAT).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Only one utility company in Great Britain offers net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The United Kingdom government is reluctant to introduce the net metering principle because of complications in paying and refunding the value added tax that is payable on electricity, but pilot projects are underway in some areas.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In Canada, some provinces have net metering programs.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In the Philippines, Net Metering scheme is governed by Republic Act 9513 (Renewable Energy Act of 2008) and its implementing rules and regulation (IRR).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The implementing body is the Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) in consultation with the National Renewable Energy Board (NREB).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Unfortunately, the scheme is not a true net metering scheme but in reality a net billing scheme.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As the Dept of Energy's Net Metering guidelines say, "Net-metering allows customers of Distribution Utilities (DUs) to install an on-site Renewable Energy (RE) facility not exceeding 100 kilowatts (kW) in capacity so they can generate electricity for their own use.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Any electricity generated that is not consumed by the customer is automatically exported to the DU's distribution system.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Thus Philippine consumers who generate their own electricity and sell their surplus to the utility are paid what is called the "generation cost" which is often less than 50% of the retail price of electricity.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering is controversial as it affects different interests on the grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] A report prepared by Peter Kind of Energy Infrastructure Advocates for the trade association Edison Electric Institute stated that distributed generation systems, like rooftop solar, present unique challenges to the future of electric utilities.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Utilities in the United States have led a largely unsuccessful campaign to eliminate net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Renewable advocates point out that while distributed solar and other energy efficiency measures do pose a challenge to electric utilities' existing business model, the benefits of distributed generation outweigh the costs, and those benefits are shared by all ratepayers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Grid benefits of private distributed solar investment include reduced need for centralizing power plants and reduced strain on the utility grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] An independent report conducted by the consulting firm Crossborder Energy found that the benefits of California's net metering program outweigh the costs to ratepayers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Those net benefits will amount to more than US$92 million annually upon the completion of the current net metering program.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] A 2012 report on the cost of net metering in the State of California, commissioned by the California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC), showed that those customers without distributed generation systems will pay US$287 in additional costs to use and maintain the grid every year by 2020.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The report also showed the net cost will amount to US$1.1 billion by 2020.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Notably, the same report found that solar customers do pay more on their power bills than what it costs the utility to serve them (Table 5, page 10: average 103% of their cost of service across the three major utilities in 2011).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Many electric utilities state that owners of generation systems do not pay the full cost of service to use the grid, thus shifting their share of the cost onto customers without distributed generation systems.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Most owners of rooftop solar or other types of distributed generation systems still rely on the grid to receive electricity from utilities at night or when their systems cannot generate sufficient power.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] A 2014 report funded by the Institute for Electric Innovation (which engages in lobbying for the benefit of its member electricity companies) claims that net metering in California produces excessively large subsidies for typical residential rooftop solar photovoltaic (PV) facilities.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] These subsidies must then be paid for by other residential customers, most of whom are less affluent than the rooftop solar PV customers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In addition, the report points out that most of these large subsidies go to the solar leasing companies, which accounted for about 75 percent of the solar PV facilities installed in 2013.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] On a nationwide basis, energy officials have debated replacement programs for net metering for several years.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of 2018, a few "replicable models" have emerged.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Utility companies have always contended that customers with solar get their bills reduced by too much under net metering, and as a result, that shifts costs for keeping up the grid infrastructure to the rest of the non-solar customers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] "The policy has led to heated state-level debates since 2003 over whether — and how — to construct a successor to the policy," according to Utility Dive.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The key challenge to constructing pricing and rebate schemes in a post-net metering environment is how to compensate rooftop solar customers fairly while not imposing costs on non-solar customers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Experts have said that a good "successor tariff," as the post-net metering policies have been called, is one that supports the growth of distributed energy resources in a way where customers and the grid get benefits from it.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Thirteen states swapped successor tariffs for retail rate net metering programs in 2017.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 2018, three more states made similar changes.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] For example, compensation in Nevada will go down over time, but today the compensation is at the retail rate (meaning, solar customers who send energy to the grid get compensated at the same rate they pay for electricity).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In Arizona, the new solar rate is ten percent below the retail rate.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The two most common successor tariffs are called "net billing" and "buy-all-sell-all" (BASA).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] "Net billing pays the retail rate for customer-consumed PV generation and a below retail rate for exported generation.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] There is considerable confusion between the terms "net metering" and "feed-in tariff" (FIT).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Feed-in tariff: generally above retail, and reduces to retail as the percentage of adopters increases.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Power purchase agreement: Compensation generally below retail, also known as a "Standard Offer Program", can be above retail, particularly in the case of solar, which tends to be generated close to peak demand.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In **market rate net metering** systems the user's energy use is priced dynamically according to some function of wholesale electric prices.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The users' meters are programmed remotely to calculate the value and are read remotely.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering applies such variable pricing to excess power produced by a qualifying system.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Market rate metering systems were implemented in California starting in 2006, and under the terms of California's net metering rules will be applicable to qualifying photovoltaic and wind systems.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Under California law the payback for surplus electricity sent to the grid must be equal to the (variable, in this case) price charged at that time.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] No credit is given for annual surplus production.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Excess generation is a separate issue from net metering, but it is normally dealt with in the same rules, because it can arise.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] If local generation offsets a portion of the demand, net metering is not used.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] If local generation exceeds demand some of the time, for example during the day, net metering is used.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] If local generation exceeds demand for the billing cycle, best practices calls for a perpetual roll over of the kilowatt-hour credits, although some regions have considered having any kWh credits expire after 36 months.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The normal definition of excess generation is annually, although the term is equally applicable monthly.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The treatment of annual excess generation (and monthly) ranges from lost, to compensation at avoided cost, to compensation at retail rate.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Left over kWh credits upon termination of service would ideally be paid at retail rate, from the consumer standpoint, and lost, from the utility standpoint, with avoided cost a minimum compromise.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Some regions allow optional payment for excess annual generation, which allows perpetual roll over or payment, at the customers choice.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Both wind and solar are inherently seasonal, and it is highly likely to use up a surplus later, unless more solar panels or a larger wind turbine have been installed than needed.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering systems can have energy storage integrated, to store some of the power locally (i.e. from the renewable energy source connected to the system) rather than selling everything to the mains electricity grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Often, the batteries used are industrial deep cycle batteries as these last for 10 to 20 years.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Other types of batteries with shorter lifespans, like Lead-acid (around 5 years) and Lithium-ion, are also still used.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Finally, nickel-iron batteries last the longest with a lifespan of up to 40 years.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] A 2017 study of solar panels with battery storage indicated an 8 to 14 percent extra consumption of electricity from charging and discharging batteries.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The financial differences are very substantial.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In Victoria, from 2009, householders were paid 60 cents for every excess kilowatt hour of energy fed into the state electricity grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This was around three times the retail price for electricity at that time.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] However, subsequent state governments reduced the feed-in in several updates, until in 2016 the feed-in is as low as 5 cents per kilowatt hour.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In Queensland starting in 2008, the Solar Bonus Scheme pays 44 cents for every excess kilowatt hour of energy fed into the state electricity grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This is around three times the current retail price for electricity.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] However, from 2012, the Queensland feed in tariff has been reduced to 6-10 cents per kilowatt hour depending on which electricity retailer the customer has signed up with.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Australian smart grid technologist, Steve Hoy, originated the opposing concept of "True Zero", as opposed to "Net Zero", to express the emerging capability to trace electricity through net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The meter allows consumers to trace their electricity to the source, making clean energy more accessible to everyone.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Ontario allows net metering for systems up to 500 kW, however credits can only be carried for 12 consecutive months.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Should a consumer establish a credit where they generate more than they consume for 8 months and use up the credits in the 10th month, then the 12-month period begins again from the date that the next credit is shown on an invoice.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Any unused credits remaining at the end of 12 consecutive months of a consumer being in a credit situation are cleared at the end of that billing.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Areas of British Columbia serviced by BC Hydro are allowed net metering for up to 100 kW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] At each annual anniversary on March 1 the customer is paid a market price, calculated as daily average mid-Columbia price for a previous year.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] FortisBC which serves an area in South Central BC also allows net-metering for up to 50 kW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Customers are paid their existing retail rate for any net energy they produce.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The City of New Westminster, which has its own electrical utility, also allows net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] New Brunswick allows net metering for installations up to 100 kW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Credits from excess generated power can be carried over until March at which time any excess credits are lost.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] SaskPower allows net metering for installations up to 100 kW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Credits from excess generated power can be carried over until the customer's annual anniversary date, at which time any excess credits are lost.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In Nova Scotia, in 2015, 43 residences and businesses began using solar panels for electricity.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] These customers’ solar systems are net metered.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of 2024, 7000 Nova Scotians had installed solar.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of 31 December 2024, there were 45 active commercial net metering generators totalling 4.1 MW, and 11 102 legacy net metering customers (including 58 with wind, 1with hydro, and 6 six "other/combination") with a nameplate capacity of 97.7 MW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This was over double the projection of 39 MW published in 2020 for 2025.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Denmark established net-metering for privately owned PV systems in mid-1998 for a pilot-period of four years.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 2002 the net-metering scheme was extended another four years up to end of 2006.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net-metering has proved to be a cheap, easy to administer and effective way of stimulating the deployment of PV in Denmark; however the relative short time window of the arrangement has so far prevented it from reaching its full potential.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] During the political negotiations in the fall of 2005 the net-metering for privately owned PV systems was made permanent.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The Netherlands has net-metering since 2004.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Initially there was a limit of 3000 kWh per year.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Later this limit was increased to 5000 kWh.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The limit was removed altogether on January 1, 2014.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Italy offers a support scheme, mixing net-metering and a well segmented premium FiT.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Slovenia has annual net-metering since January 2016 for up to 11 kVA.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In a calendar year up to 10 MVA can be installed in the country.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 2010, Spain, net-metering has been proposed by the *Asociación de la Industria Fotovoltaica* (ASIF) to promote renewable electricity, without requiring additional economic support.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net-metering for privately owned systems will be established in 2019, after Royal Decree 244/2019 was accepted by the government on April 5.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Some form of net metering is now proposed by *Électricité de France*.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] According to their website, energy produced by home-owners is bought at a higher price than what is charged as consumers.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Hence, some recommend to sell all energy produced, and buy back all energy needed at a lower price.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The price has been fixed for 20 years by the government.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Ireland is planning to implement a net metering system, under the "Micro-generation Support Scheme".
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Under the proposed scheme, micro-generators can sell 30% of the excess electricity they produce and export it back to the grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The price that electricity will be sold at is being formulated during the consultation process.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Poland has introduced net metering for private and commercial renewable energy sources of up to 50 kW in 2015.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Under this legislation energy sent to grid must be used within one year from feed-in, otherwise it is considered as lost.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The amount of energy that was exported and can be taken back by the user is subtracted by 20% for installations up to 10 kW, or by 30% for installations up to 50 kW.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This legislation guarantees that this net metering policy will be kept for a minimum of 15 years from the moment of registering renewable energy source.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This legislation together with government subsidies for microgeneration created a substantial boost in installations of PV systems in Poland.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Portugal has a very limited form of "net-metering" that is constrained to 15 minute periods where the excess injected in the grid is not compensated when above the consumption from the grid within each 15 minute period.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Only the injected energy up to the consumed energy within the same 15 minute period is netted out of the final monthly bill.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In fact the old analog electricity meters that would allow for true net-metering are immediately replaced when a consumer installs solar pv.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Almost every state in India has implemented net-metering, wherein, the consumers are allowed to sell the surplus energy generated by their solar system to the grid and get compensated for the same.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] However, the net-metering policy is not common throughout the country and varies from state to state.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] To avail of net-metering in the country, the consumer is required to submit an application with the local electricity distribution company along with the planned rooftop solar project and requisite fee.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The distribution company reviews the application and the feasibility of the solar project, which is either approved or rejected.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] If approved, another application for registration of the rooftop is submitted to the distribution company.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] An agreement is signed between the consumer and the company, and the net-meter is installed.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The Indian states of Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh have started the implementation of net metering, and the policy was announced by the respective state electricity boards in 2014.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] After review and inspection by the electricity board, a bidirectional meter is installed.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Applications are taken up for up to 30% of the distribution transformer capacity on a first-come, first-served basis and technical feasibility.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Since September 2015, Maharashtra state (MERC) has also had a net metering policy and consumers have started installation of Solar Rooftop Grid Tie Net metering systems.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] MERC Policy allows up to 40% transformer capacity to be on Solar net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The various DISCOMs in Maharashtra namely MSEDCL, Tata, Reliance and Torrent Power are expected to support net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of now MSEDCL does not use the TOD (Time of The Day differential) charging tariffs for residential consumers and net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Export and import units are considered at par for calculating Net Units and bill amount.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering is a policy by many states in the United States designed to help the adoption of renewable energy.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering was pioneered in the United States as a way to allow solar and wind to provide electricity whenever available and allow use of that electricity whenever it was needed, beginning with utilities in Idaho in 1980, and in Arizona in 1981.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In 1983, Minnesota passed the first state net metering law.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] As of March 2015, 44 states and Washington, D.C. have developed mandatory net metering rules for at least some utilities.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] However, although the states' rules are clear, few utilities actually compensate at full retail rates.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Net metering policies are determined by states, which have set policies varying on a number of key dimensions.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 required state electricity regulators to "consider" (but not necessarily implement) rules that mandate public electric utilities make net metering available to their customers upon request.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Several legislative bills have been proposed to institute a federal standard limit on net metering.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] 729, which sets a net metering cap at 2% of forecasted aggregate customer peak demand, to H.R.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] 1945, which has no aggregate cap, but does limit residential users to 10 kW, a low limit compared to many states, such as New Mexico, with an 80,000 kW limit, or states such as Arizona, Colorado, New Jersey, and Ohio, which limit as a percentage of load.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Under this arrangement, two uni-directional meters are installed—one records electricity drawn from the grid, and the other records excess electricity generated and fed into the grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The user pays retail rate for the electricity they use, and the power provider purchases their excess generation at its avoided cost (wholesale rate).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] There may be a significant difference between the retail rate the user pays and the power provider's avoided cost.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Some jurisdictions, such as Germany, Spain, the province of Ontario in Canada, and some states in the United States, compensate the generated electricity at a fixed rate, in a scheme called feed-in tariff (FIT).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] With the FIT, customers get paid for any electricity they generate from renewable energy on their premises.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The actual electricity being generated is counted on a separate meter, not just the surplus they feed to the grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Germany once paid several times the retail rate for solar but has reduced the rates drastically while actual installation of solar has grown exponentially at the same time due to reduced cost of solar installations.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Wind energy, in contrast, only receives around a half of the domestic retail rate, because the German system pays what each source costs (including a reasonable profit margin).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Another method of producing power to the grid is through **virtual net metering** (also called peer-to-peer (P2P) energy trading, wheeling and sometimes local energy trading).
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Peer-to-peer energy trading is a novel paradigm of power system operation, where sellers can generate their own energy in dwellings, offices and factories, and share it with each other locally.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Several companies offering virtual net metering use blockchain technology.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Sources that produce direct current, such as solar panels, must be coupled with an electrical inverter to convert the output to alternating current for use with conventional appliances.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] The phase of the outgoing power must be synchronized with the grid, and a mechanism must be included to disconnect the feed in the event of grid failure.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] This is for safety – for example, workers repairing downed power lines must be protected from "downstream" sources, in addition to being disconnected from the main "upstream" distribution grid.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Although a small generator lacks the power to energize a loaded line, this can happen if the line is isolated from other loads.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] Solar inverters are designed for safety – while one inverter could not energize a line, a thousand might.
[src:ami-metering/net-metering] In addition, electrical workers are trained to treat every line as though it was live, even when they know it should be safe.
